english:
  title: Preface to Miscellaneous Poems on the Southern Refuge
  author: Lee Yu
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The jade of Harmony does not always emerge from Kunlun, nor does the thousand-li steed always come from the northern fields. Among all things endowed with nature by Heaven, none is more precious than man, yet the qualities of loyalty and integrity, of talent and virtue, are the rarest to find. How much more so in distant frontier lands.

    Master Chung of Three Peaks was my friend from the same examination year. In the winter of the year Imyin of the Zhizheng era, our Minister Hong presided over the civil service examinations with the utmost care in selecting scholars, and Master Chung passed among them. At that time, he was young and sharp-minded; his writings were swift and original, so that his peers regarded him differently, knowing he would not settle for mediocrity. After he observed mourning for his parents for three years in his home village, he shut his door to study the Classics, reading widely through the philosophical texts, analyzing heterodox teachings. He investigated both the distant—heaven and earth, rivers and mountains—and the intimate—human nature, moral principle, light as sun and moon, subtle as spirits and gods—as well as human relations and daily customs, the transformations of imperial rule and governance, and even the gains and losses in law and institutions, the successes and failures in ritual and music, leaving nothing unexamined in his meticulous investigation and profound reflection.

    It happened that our former sovereign, seeking the refined and cultured everywhere to illumine civilization, placed special emphasis on the rituals of the ancestral temples and the canons of music and ceremony. Finding him difficult to match, he believed that Master Chung's vast learning could illuminate moral relations and cultivate talent, while his penetrating discernment could grasp the foundations of ritual and music and harmonize the divine and human realms. Thus he appointed him as Doctor of the State Academy and Doctor of the Imperial Sacrifices, advancing him even to the position of Director of Ceremonies—an unprecedented honor indeed.

    Last summer, Master Chung, acting with loyalty and directness, remonstrated on matters of state, and incurred the displeasure of those in power. He was exiled to the south of the lake. I visited his dwelling many times during this period. Master Chung rented a single room, surrounded on all sides by books, passing through summer and winter with but one robe of hemp and one of silk, eating simple vegetable fare morning and evening. He discoursed on the wisdom of sages and the way of benevolence and virtue, illuminating the distinction between heavenly principle and human desire. Many scholars of the southern regions gathered around him. In the intervals between these discussions, he composed numerous poems and essays, arranging them into a collection which he titled *Miscellaneous Poems of the Southern Refuge*, revealing his aspirations. His prose matches the ancients without shame, and his verse in varied lengths achieves both elegance and naturalness, gathering the strengths of many schools into a style uniquely his own. Not a word of resentment or bitterness over his banishment mars these pages; rather, his loyalty and moral integrity shine forth, flooding through his language. Is this not the mark of one who truly understands what matters and what does not?

    Generally, men rejoice in gain and grieve in loss—such is human nature. But Master Chung is not thus. His banishment came only through his loyalty; his acceptance of it flows only from his faith in moral principle. He regards floating clouds of wealth and rank as dust, sees mountain retreat and court service as equally indifferent, holds life and death, fortune and misfortune with unwavering resolve. As if he had heard the Way at dawn and were willing to die at dusk, as if he had abandoned life to preserve righteousness—only one whose faith in the Way runs deep and whose self-knowledge is clear could achieve this. Does not the saying go, "To remain untroubled when one's rightness is not recognized"? Surely this speaks of Master Chung.

    Alas, though our Eastern lands lie in distant reaches, their mountains and waters rival all under Heaven in beauty. The vital forces gathered here have produced countless talents in both letters and arms throughout the ages. Yet I wonder—does Heaven send Master Chung now to make his writings resound through an age? To transmit the learning of the Way to mankind? Or to rectify a declining world and encourage degenerate customs through the power of his noble character and steadfast integrity? All three would be worthy causes. I, lacking skill in words, have presumed to write this preface simply because I cherish that loyalty and virtue, that talent and integrity, have taken root in our soil. And I hope that later gentlemen who admire the ancients will through these words come to know the true nature of Master Chung.
  footnotes:
    - The 'jade of Harmony' (和氏璧) and the 'thousand-li steed' are classical allusions to rare and precious things, establishing the theme that exceptional virtue is even rarer than exceptional material goods.
    - The reference to 'sages hearing the Way at dawn and being willing to die at dusk' alludes to Confucius's teaching about the highest wisdom and virtue.
    - The quotation about remaining untroubled when one's rightness is not recognized reflects Confucian ideals of maintaining moral integrity regardless of external circumstances.
